️ The "Ghost Image" & "Digital Dongle" Manifest (April 2026)

1. The Stealth Container
Format: Sparse Custom Binary Vault (.bin).
Location: Hidden deep in a non-indexed system folder (e.g., AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\WebCache\).
Dynamic Sizing: Uses Sparse File technology. A 10GB decoy vault occupies ~50MB on your SSD, visually masking the real vault's size.
Visibility: Looks like a corrupted or locked system database to Windows and third-party tools.

2. The Redundancy Grid (Multi-Image Sync)
Primary: Local NVMe (High-speed access).
Secondary: SATA SSD (Stable backup).
Physical Key: Your Flash Drive (The "Air-Gap" copy).
Logic: The Rust app treats these files as a single pool, keeping backups synchronized.

3. The Security Stack & Digital Dongle
Encryption: Native ChaCha20-Poly1305 with Custom Header Chunking.
Key Derivation (Slot A): Argon2 hashing of a traditional Master Password combined with a randomly generated 16-byte vault salt.
Key Derivation (Slot B - The "Dongle"): BLAKE3 fast-hashing of a physical Image file (.jpg, .png) dragged onto the UI.
Steganography Vault (The Appended Payload): An encrypted vault can be injected directly into the EOF (End of File) marker of the Image Dongle itself. This creates a fully deniable portable vault that opens like a normal photo on any computer.
Zeroize Protocol: The Master Password, File Hash buffers, and ingested CSV Plaintext are all forcibly zeroed out of RAM the microsecond they are used.

4. The Execution Blueprint (Rust)
Component          Technology                  The "Physicalist" Advantage
The Ghost Drive    ImDisk / RAM Disk           Temporary "Clean Room" for the CSV. Data never touches the SSD "naked."
The Container      Sparse std::fs              No wasted space. The vault grows only as your password list grows.
The Eraser         Zeroize + Shred             Wipes the RAM and "incinerates" the Ghost Drive after the gobble.
The Dongle         BLAKE3 + Appended Payload   Uses the physical bytes of an image as an auth token, while safely carrying the encrypted vault payload at its tail.
Core Affinity      WinAPI / core_affinity      Pins execution explicitly to the last processor core (and its threads), keeping the UI off Core 0.

5. The "10% Admin" Workflow (Dynamic Edition)
Mount the Ghost: App creates a 5MB RAM drive (Z:).
Unlock the Vault: Type the password (Slot A) OR drag-and-drop the secret "Key" file (Slot B) into the app window.
Arbitrary File Capture: Drag and drop files directly into the UI or drop them into the Z:/ drive to encrypt and store them. The UI partitions Passwords at the top and Files at the bottom for a clean look.
Export the Loot: Browser saves passwords.csv to Z:/.
The Gobble: Rust app detects the file via `notify`, extracts the credentials to RAM, encrypts them to the `.bin` vault, and instantly shreds the original CSV.
The Stealth Hide: User closes the app or locks the vault. RAM is cleared, and the .bin file remains fully encrypted.

📍 CURRENT STATUS & NEXT STEPS (SAVE POINT)
-------------------------------------------
[X] Sparse Decoy Generation: Implemented. Created 10GB stealth files consuming ~50MB of physical disk space, injected with CSPRNG entropy via the `rand` crate to mimic ChaCha20 encrypted noise.
[X] The Gobble (File Watcher): Active. Monitoring the RAM Drive for CSV payloads.
[X] Anti-Deadlock File Lock: Mastered. Using `share_mode(1)` (FILE_SHARE_READ) to securely lock the file from writes while allowing Windows Defender to peek, bypassing OS kernel deadlocks.
[X] Secure Shredder: Active. Overwriting the intercepted CSV with `0xFF` in 4KB zeroized chunks, forcing a hardware flush (`sync_all`), and aggressively deleting the unlinked file.
[X] CSV Ingestion: Implemented. Successfully parsing variable-schema CSV rows into memory using `serde`.
[X] Vault Encryption & Storage: Implemented. Custom `GVLT` header architecture with Argon2 salt storage and military-grade ChaCha20-Poly1305 payload appends.
[X] Graphical Interface: Implemented. Cross-thread dynamic logging, live decrypted password viewing, window-close safety intercepts, and vault zeroization tools.
[X] Digital Dongle (Dependencies): Added `blake3` to the Cargo manifest for hardware-accelerated fast hashing.
[X] Drag-and-Drop File Auth: Wired up `egui` to accept dropped files on the Lock Screen, triggering the BLAKE3 hash generation.
[X] Dynamic Unlock Logic: Allowed the vault to be unlocked by seamlessly switching between an Argon2 Master Password OR a BLAKE3 physical file hash.
[X] The Redundancy Grid: Upgraded the storage engine to simultaneously sync encrypted chunks across multiple drives (Primary, Backup, and USB Flash Drive).
[X] Idle Auto-Lock: Implemented a timer that securely scrubs memory and locks the UI if the user steps away from the keyboard for too long.
[X] Switch to Bincode: Swapped out JSON serialization to tightly pack large arbitrary binary files (PDFs, images) natively without base64 bloat.
[X] UI File Partition: Split the main table view to elegantly show Passwords at the top and a Stored Files directory at the bottom.
[X] Drag & Drop File Ingestion: Expanded the `egui` drop logic to capture and securely encrypt arbitrary files into the vault grid on the fly.

